WEBVTT

01:28.463 --> 01:29.631
Oh fuck.

01:42.018 --> 01:44.813
Donald Trump
We want products
made by our own workers

01:44.896 --> 01:47.273
in our factories,
stamped with those

01:47.357 --> 01:48.858
four magnificent words...

01:52.111 --> 01:53.696
Trump
...made in the USA.

01:53.780 --> 01:55.365
Are the kids here?

01:55.448 --> 01:57.617
The kids? No, Michael.

01:57.700 --> 01:59.202
Let's go!

02:05.250 --> 02:06.668
Alright, you fucker.

02:09.128 --> 02:10.338
911
Durham 911,
what's your emergency?

02:10.421 --> 02:11.756
1810 Cedar street.

02:11.840 --> 02:12.507
-Please.
-What's wrong?

02:12.590 --> 02:14.092
My wife, she had an accident.

02:14.175 --> 02:15.218
She's still breathing

02:15.301 --> 02:16.302
What kind of accident?

02:16.386 --> 02:17.470
She fell down the stairs.

02:17.554 --> 02:19.055
She's still breathing.
Please come.

02:19.138 --> 02:20.598
-- Is she conscious?
-- What?

02:20.682 --> 02:21.724
-Is she conscious?
-No, she's not conscious.

02:21.808 --> 02:23.434
How many stairs
did she fall down?

02:23.518 --> 02:24.727
-- What?
-- How many stairs?

02:24.811 --> 02:25.728
15, 20, I don't know.

02:25.812 --> 02:27.856
Please get somebody here
right away. Please.

02:27.939 --> 02:29.065
...dispatching the ambulance

02:29.149 --> 02:30.483
while I ask you questions.

02:33.778 --> 02:34.737
911 operator: Durham 911,
what is your emergency?

02:34.821 --> 02:36.739
Where are they?

02:36.823 --> 02:39.242
This is 1810 Cedar Street.

02:39.325 --> 02:41.995
She's not breathing. Please.
Please, will you hurry up.

02:42.078 --> 02:44.455
911 operator:
Sir, calm down,
they're on the way.

02:44.539 --> 02:47.167
Can you tell me for sure
she's not breathing.

02:47.250 --> 02:48.918
Sir. Sir?

03:02.974 --> 03:04.309
That party was lame.

03:04.392 --> 03:07.812
I hope no one saw us
walk out together.

03:11.232 --> 03:13.443
Are your parents gonna be up?

03:13.526 --> 03:15.695
Yeah. But they won't
even see us come in.

03:15.778 --> 03:17.780
-Okay.

03:30.168 --> 03:31.544
Todd?

03:33.087 --> 03:34.213
Todd, wake up!

03:35.840 --> 03:37.800
What the fuck?

03:39.594 --> 03:40.803
The fuck!

03:54.734 --> 03:56.444
Hey, wh-what's going on here?

03:56.527 --> 03:56.986
Do you live here?

03:57.070 --> 03:59.030
No, my, my parents do.

03:59.113 --> 04:00.239
Wh-what's going on?

04:00.323 --> 04:02.158
-Have you been drinking?
-What?

04:02.241 --> 04:02.992
No. I mean,
yeah, we just came

04:03.076 --> 04:05.161
from a Christmas party
down the street.

04:05.244 --> 04:07.121
-Todd? Todd?
-She family, too?

04:07.205 --> 04:08.665
-No, no, I'm--
-No, she's one
of my friends.

04:08.748 --> 04:09.999
Can you please
just let me in.

04:10.083 --> 04:10.583
Alright, but just you.

04:10.667 --> 04:13.002
Thank you.

04:13.753 --> 04:16.172
Dad! Kathleen!

04:16.255 --> 04:17.131
Hey.

04:17.215 --> 04:18.675
Hey, what's going on?

04:19.634 --> 04:20.969
Hey, what's going on?

04:22.220 --> 04:23.930
Is this your home, sir?

04:24.013 --> 04:26.224
-Yeah, wha-what happened?

04:26.307 --> 04:28.059
Dad! Dad!
Dad! Dad!

04:28.142 --> 04:30.979
Dad, what happened?
What happened

04:31.062 --> 04:32.981
Are you okay?
What happened to Kathleen?

04:33.064 --> 04:34.482
Kathleen...

04:36.567 --> 04:38.361
-Something's wrong.
-Dad, what happened?

04:38.444 --> 04:40.071
Something's wrong, god!

04:40.154 --> 04:40.571
Oh my god.

04:49.163 --> 04:51.541
-Is she dead?
-I'm afraid so, son.

04:52.834 --> 04:54.836
What, what happened?

04:54.919 --> 04:56.254
Your dad called 911,

04:56.337 --> 04:58.214
said his wife
fell down the stairs.

05:00.800 --> 05:01.551
She... she fell?

05:01.634 --> 05:03.511
Ohh.

05:04.012 --> 05:06.139
This is, um...

05:06.222 --> 05:09.058
Is there a way
to bring her back?

05:09.142 --> 05:10.226
No. She's gone.

05:22.155 --> 05:23.239
Dad.

05:27.160 --> 05:27.702
Kathleen's dead, Dad.

05:27.785 --> 05:30.329
-No.
-Dad! Dad!

05:32.206 --> 05:33.124
-Dad.
-No! No!

05:33.207 --> 05:36.544
Sir! Get him off her, now!

05:36.627 --> 05:38.463
No!

05:38.546 --> 05:40.506
Sir, you're gonna have to-- sir!

05:40.590 --> 05:42.050
Okay, sir,
you need to let go.

05:42.133 --> 05:43.259
Son, he's gonna have
to let go.

05:43.342 --> 05:46.512
-Sir, now!

05:46.596 --> 05:48.931
Dad. Dad, you have to let go.

05:49.015 --> 05:50.808
Please, Dad.
You have to let go.

05:50.892 --> 05:51.934
Sit him down!

05:56.355 --> 05:57.940
I got you, I got you.

05:58.024 --> 06:00.860
I've got you, I've got you.

06:00.943 --> 06:03.279
Officer! Yeah, I need
some help in here.

06:03.362 --> 06:04.781
Can I get some assistance,
please?

06:07.909 --> 06:09.911
Is that your mother?

06:09.994 --> 06:12.371
It's, uh,
it's my stepmother, yeah.

06:12.455 --> 06:14.457
Sarge, what's your ETA?

06:14.540 --> 06:17.001
-Copy, I'm with the husband
and stepson

06:17.085 --> 06:18.961
in the kitchen
standing by.

06:19.045 --> 06:20.505
-Coroner's en route.
-What happens now?

06:20.588 --> 06:22.381
We've got
some more guys coming.

06:22.465 --> 06:23.341
You and your dad
should just stay there.

06:23.424 --> 06:26.552
When is the last time
you saw your mom?

06:26.636 --> 06:26.969
I saw her tonight.

06:28.429 --> 06:32.308
I'm really worried about him.
Jesus Christ!

06:32.391 --> 06:34.268
Officer
Can someone quiet
those dogs down?

06:34.352 --> 06:35.853
Were they arguing?

06:35.937 --> 06:37.688
No, they weren't arguing,
they were, they were drinking,

06:37.772 --> 06:39.023
they were laughing.

06:41.442 --> 06:43.820
Do you guys have, like,
a grief counselor or something?

06:43.903 --> 06:45.363
We can make a request.

06:45.446 --> 06:47.990
If you don't think
he can control himself,

06:48.074 --> 06:49.158
-you can go outside...
-Can't control himself?

06:49.242 --> 06:50.993
...and get some air.

06:51.077 --> 06:52.787
Here. Let's,
let's get you cleaned up.

06:53.913 --> 06:55.414
Come on.

06:55.498 --> 06:57.041
I got you. I got you.

06:57.125 --> 06:57.875
I got you.

07:02.046 --> 07:04.423
What...
what happened, Dad? Huh?

07:06.759 --> 07:09.679
Uh, we were outside...

07:09.762 --> 07:11.556
we were...

07:15.768 --> 07:17.270
and then she came in...

07:19.272 --> 07:21.983
and then I came in, uh...

07:22.817 --> 07:24.485
and I found her,

07:28.447 --> 07:30.950
Come on, Dad, let's, let's
get you cleaned up. Here.

07:32.702 --> 07:34.412
Alright, Sarge, in here.

07:34.495 --> 07:36.747
That's him by the sink, sir.

07:37.999 --> 07:39.500
I'm Sergeant Borden.

07:39.584 --> 07:42.086
I need you to stop
doing that right now.

07:42.170 --> 07:43.546
Turn off the water, please.

07:43.629 --> 07:46.883
Okay, fine, but I've asked
for a grief counselor.

07:46.966 --> 07:48.593
Is there a grief counselor
coming or not?

07:49.552 --> 07:51.179
Sergeant
Mr. Peterson,

07:51.262 --> 07:52.513
the house has now
been declared a crime scene.

07:54.974 --> 07:57.268
We'll need to keep you all
here until further notice.

08:22.835 --> 08:23.794
-Ahh!
-Oh!

08:26.047 --> 08:27.423
Okay, come on.

08:27.506 --> 08:29.217
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

08:30.885 --> 08:32.178
Okay.

08:32.261 --> 08:33.804
Just a little for you.

08:35.306 --> 08:37.099
Thank you!

08:37.183 --> 08:38.100
A little more for me.
Just a little, yeah.

08:38.184 --> 08:40.436
-You sure?
-Mm-hmm.

08:40.519 --> 08:42.563
Okay.
Now speech.

08:42.647 --> 08:43.940
-Speech, speech, speech.
-No.

08:46.275 --> 08:49.570
Well... thank you, Mom.

08:51.447 --> 08:54.659
For... for everything

08:54.742 --> 09:00.623
and for that,
like, amazing note.

09:00.706 --> 09:03.918
I'm expecting you and Dad
to visit me in San Francisco.

09:04.001 --> 09:05.294
Yes, of course.

09:05.378 --> 09:07.129
-Of course.
-I love you.

09:07.213 --> 09:09.131
Wait, you're,
you're starting without me?

09:09.215 --> 09:10.841
There you are. Yes!
And we're about to eat too.

09:10.925 --> 09:12.635
You'd think he'd get home
from the gym on time

09:12.718 --> 09:13.552
at least once.

09:13.636 --> 09:17.181
Dad, you still smell.
Go have a shower.

09:17.265 --> 09:18.307
-I'll save you a glass.
-Hey, Dad?

09:18.391 --> 09:21.644
Okay, Margaret, go get your,
uh, your mother's China

09:21.727 --> 09:22.478
and grab the good
linen napkins from upstairs,

09:22.562 --> 09:26.190
because this is
a special occasion.

09:26.274 --> 09:28.234
Her baby girl
is going to college.

09:28.317 --> 09:30.319
Oh!

09:30.403 --> 09:32.613
-I love you!
-Oh, I want some!

09:34.991 --> 09:36.242
Alright.
Go upstairs already.

09:36.325 --> 09:37.702
You're gonna make me cry.

09:39.537 --> 09:40.204
And get your brother.

09:40.288 --> 09:42.373
Todd!

09:42.456 --> 09:43.874
Todd!

09:45.209 --> 09:47.503
Don't give me that look.
And get the salad bowl.

09:49.547 --> 09:51.507
You know, you never
wrote me a special note

09:51.591 --> 09:53.050
when I went away.

09:53.134 --> 09:54.719
Yeah. Well, it's different,
you know that.

09:56.679 --> 09:57.680
Plus...

09:57.763 --> 10:00.725
I don't overshare with them
the way I do with you.

10:00.808 --> 10:01.642
-They don't know my pain.

10:08.774 --> 10:10.276
Todd! Todd!

10:10.359 --> 10:12.862
What? I'm on the phone!

10:12.945 --> 10:14.905
Dinner's almost ready.

10:14.989 --> 10:16.949
No, Nate, what I'm saying
is that we could be making

10:17.033 --> 10:18.242
so much more on this
back-to-school stuff.

10:18.326 --> 10:20.369
Nate
We should just bully
them into buying stuff.

10:20.453 --> 10:21.996
Right. Right, exactly.

10:22.079 --> 10:22.538
I mean, it could be funny,
even like...

10:24.498 --> 10:27.001
a bag with wheels
is for losers.

10:27.084 --> 10:28.627
And then these are
the best backpacks to buy

10:28.711 --> 10:29.045
and then links
where to buy them.

10:29.128 --> 10:31.047
-Hey.
-Right.

10:31.130 --> 10:32.340
Oh. Hey.

10:32.423 --> 10:34.508
Hey, one sec, Nate.
What's up?

10:34.592 --> 10:36.385
Dinner's ready.

10:36.469 --> 10:38.471
Alright, I'm just
finishing a call.

10:38.554 --> 10:40.389
I'll be in my office.

10:42.641 --> 10:44.435
Nate-Nate, we got
this dinner for Martha.

10:44.518 --> 10:46.270
Let me, let me
call you back later.

11:13.339 --> 11:15.591
-Todd, get the cup.
-Oh, okay.

11:17.134 --> 11:18.302
-Oh!

11:18.386 --> 11:20.346
-How was that?
-That was...

11:21.430 --> 11:22.807
You got to, you know...

11:27.311 --> 11:28.521
Alright.

11:28.604 --> 11:31.649
So to continue
the tradition

11:31.732 --> 11:34.443
started by Uncle Bill
and my dear old papa,

11:34.527 --> 11:36.779
what the Brits call
"passin' the loving cup"...

11:36.862 --> 11:40.741
-...but with a Peterson twist.

11:44.870 --> 11:46.414
-Kathleen.
-Yes.

11:46.497 --> 11:49.125
-You first.
-Oh god, okay.

11:49.208 --> 11:51.293
Pass her down.

11:51.377 --> 11:52.670
Okay.

11:52.753 --> 11:55.131
Um, I'd like
to make a toast

11:56.382 --> 12:00.636
to... our beautiful
daughter Martha.

12:02.721 --> 12:04.515
No matter what color
your hair is...

12:04.598 --> 12:05.808
How about blue?

12:05.891 --> 12:07.852
Blue, green. Whatever.
-Good idea.

12:09.019 --> 12:10.312
You are beautiful.

12:11.647 --> 12:12.940
And you're my daughter.

12:14.400 --> 12:16.527
Every day is going
to be an adventure.

12:17.445 --> 12:21.907
So always stop
and think and appreciate

12:21.991 --> 12:23.325
when you're having
a really good day.

12:23.409 --> 12:24.326
You need to think
to yourself,

12:24.410 --> 12:25.327
"This is one of
the happiest days of my life,"

12:25.411 --> 12:28.831
so you can retrieve it

12:28.914 --> 12:30.166
and bring it to the front
of your mind.

12:30.249 --> 12:32.668
And treasure it.

12:32.751 --> 12:35.838
Lean on it when
you're having a bad time.

12:35.921 --> 12:40.050
Because there are
so many better days ahead.

12:42.636 --> 12:44.346
-To Martha.
-To Martha.

12:44.430 --> 12:47.266
-Okay, here.
-Yep.

12:48.267 --> 12:51.312
To... Mom.

12:52.354 --> 12:56.066
I know we'll be gone,

12:56.150 --> 12:58.444
but we're always here
for you...

12:58.527 --> 13:00.196
the way that
you've been for us.

13:00.279 --> 13:01.614
Thank you.

13:01.697 --> 13:03.199
-I love you.
-I love you.

13:03.282 --> 13:04.658
-To Mom.
-To Mom.

13:04.742 --> 13:06.076
Kathleen!

13:08.120 --> 13:08.704
I'll go.

13:11.499 --> 13:12.791
-Got it?
-Yeah.

13:15.294 --> 13:16.378
To Dad.

13:17.296 --> 13:18.547
Uh...

13:20.591 --> 13:22.301
Thank you for always
being there for me.

13:24.595 --> 13:27.598
May you succeed
in politics

13:27.681 --> 13:30.392
the way you succeeded
in writing.

13:30.476 --> 13:32.061
-To Dad.
-Dad.

13:32.144 --> 13:33.312
-To Michael.
-Thank you.

13:35.648 --> 13:37.900
To my brother Clayton.

13:37.983 --> 13:39.735
I know the last few years
haven't been the easiest
for you--

13:39.818 --> 13:42.279
Todd, Todd, we don't talk
about spring break, right?

13:42.363 --> 13:44.406
Alright.

13:44.490 --> 13:47.243
Um, I'm so proud of you.

13:49.036 --> 13:49.745
Back to school
and everything.

13:52.206 --> 13:53.832
To Clayton.

13:53.916 --> 13:55.584
-And to Becky. To Becky.
-And Becky.

13:55.668 --> 13:57.211
-Clayton.
-Becky.

13:57.294 --> 13:58.420
-Caitlin.
-Thank you.

14:01.006 --> 14:01.799
Um...

14:03.759 --> 14:08.597
to a wonderful
school year for Martha.

14:08.681 --> 14:10.599
-That toast sucked.

14:11.475 --> 14:13.936
Okay. 'Cause your speech
was amazing.

14:14.019 --> 14:16.063
I hope somebody
recorded it for posterity.

14:18.774 --> 14:20.693
Martha, I love you.

14:20.776 --> 14:24.405
I hope you have
the best next year.

14:24.488 --> 14:26.407
You'll be dancing
on a big stage someday.

14:26.490 --> 14:27.366
-Love you, Caitlin.
-Love you.

14:27.449 --> 14:30.452
-- To Martha again.
-- To Martha again.

14:30.536 --> 14:30.869
Mike's turn.

14:38.460 --> 14:39.420
Hmm.

14:40.546 --> 14:41.922
Michael, what's going on?

14:42.006 --> 14:42.339
Are you speechless?

14:42.423 --> 14:44.550
No. No. Never.

14:44.633 --> 14:46.885
-Yeah, never.
-Okay.

14:49.388 --> 14:53.183
This toast is
to all of us.

14:53.267 --> 14:56.145
Now, I think there are not
many families--

14:56.228 --> 14:57.271
Well, I know, I know
there are not many families

14:57.354 --> 14:59.565
out there like us.

14:59.648 --> 15:01.317
We're not perfect,
god knows,

15:01.400 --> 15:03.861
but we stick together.

15:05.738 --> 15:07.406
And we love each other.

15:07.865 --> 15:09.325
And so...

15:10.367 --> 15:13.329
to us.

15:13.412 --> 15:14.246
-To us.
-To the Petersons.

15:14.330 --> 15:15.831
-The Petersons.

15:15.914 --> 15:17.374
-To the Ratliffs.
-And the Atwater.

15:23.797 --> 15:25.215
Mm.

15:38.270 --> 15:40.230
Hello?

15:41.023 --> 15:42.900
Uncle Bill.

15:43.651 --> 15:43.984
Kathleen's dead.

15:48.405 --> 15:50.324
Bill?

15:54.286 --> 15:55.871
Bill, are you there?

15:56.580 --> 15:59.124
What happened?

15:59.208 --> 15:59.917
Dad was outside and, uh...

16:02.002 --> 16:03.462
when he, um...

16:04.963 --> 16:07.466
when he came in, he found her
at the bottom of the stairs.

16:09.802 --> 16:11.929
I think she was pretty
shitfaced and fell.

16:12.638 --> 16:14.098
Oh god.

16:14.181 --> 16:15.933
And they've sequestered us
in Dad's office.

16:16.016 --> 16:17.059
I mean, they won't even let
my friend go pee by herself.

16:17.142 --> 16:20.104
They're, they're calling
this whole thing a crime scene.

16:21.647 --> 16:22.815
Is this normal?

16:22.898 --> 16:24.733
It's absolutely not normal.

16:25.984 --> 16:28.362
Kathleen had
a meeting this morning.

16:28.445 --> 16:30.364
We should let them know.

16:30.447 --> 16:31.615
Dad's in there
talking to himself.

16:31.699 --> 16:34.868
Tell Mike
not to say anything.

16:34.952 --> 16:37.162
Anybody wants to talk
to either of you guys,

16:37.246 --> 16:38.038
tell 'em your attorney
is on the way.

16:39.748 --> 16:40.999
Okay.

16:41.083 --> 16:42.751
Don't-don't don't say a word.

16:42.835 --> 16:45.170
Don't say a word.

16:45.254 --> 16:47.297
Is there somewhere
you guys can go?

16:47.381 --> 16:50.134
I mean, we could probably
go to Larry's next door.

16:51.301 --> 16:52.761
If they let us.

16:52.845 --> 16:53.929
I'm going to get on
the first flight I can.

16:54.012 --> 16:56.348
I'll get you guys
out of there.

16:57.516 --> 16:58.767
Love you.

16:59.935 --> 17:01.645
Okay. I love you too.

17:17.703 --> 17:18.912
Who else is here?

17:18.996 --> 17:21.957
Michael, the son,
and his friend.

17:22.040 --> 17:23.751
Did anyone make
a statement?

17:23.834 --> 17:25.836
Nothing official,
but the son's friend said

17:25.919 --> 17:26.962
she was here earlier.

17:27.045 --> 17:27.671
I asked if she witnessed
any fighting

17:27.755 --> 17:29.590
or anything like that.

17:29.673 --> 17:31.842
She said
everything seemed fine.

17:31.925 --> 17:34.595
She didn't actually
see her, though.

17:36.847 --> 17:39.099
Said she heard the wife
laughing in the other room,

17:39.183 --> 17:40.142
but that's it.

17:43.395 --> 17:45.355
Alright.

17:54.072 --> 17:55.324
Mr. Peterson,

17:55.407 --> 17:57.159
I'm Lieutenant Investigator
Art Holland.

17:57.242 --> 17:59.328
This is a warrant granting
the Durham Police Department

17:59.411 --> 18:02.581
and all related agencies
the right to search your home

18:02.664 --> 18:04.166
and your premises
for any evidence

18:04.249 --> 18:06.877
related to the death
of Mrs. Kathleen Peterson.

18:07.461 --> 18:08.712
Do you understand?

18:12.132 --> 18:14.384
Please instruct everyone
they're allowed

18:14.468 --> 18:16.637
to re-enter the home
and commence the search.

18:17.721 --> 18:19.973
We will need your car keys
for your vehicles,

18:20.057 --> 18:22.059
and we'll need to collect
your clothing for evidence now.

18:23.143 --> 18:24.937
Alright, we're good to go.

18:25.020 --> 18:25.646
All teams move in.

18:45.124 --> 18:47.042
Hello.

18:47.125 --> 18:50.921
Uh, morning, Jim,
I'm sorry to call you so early.

18:51.839 --> 18:53.465
That's okay.
What's up?

18:53.549 --> 18:57.010
Art -
